    "narrative_anchors": {
      "dobes_heist": {
        "significance": "9 shots vs 29. .966 save percentage. The L1 drought ending was\nclutch storytelling, but the actual reason MTL advances is a 24-year-old\nrookie in his first playoff series. Dobes was the canonical\n\"stand-on-your-head\" performance of the 2026 playoffs.\n"
      },
      "l1_drought_ends": {
        "significance": "Six games of 0 5v5 goals for Suzuki-Caufield-Slafkovsky. The first\ngoal of Game 7, late P1, came from Suzuki off a Guhle-Anderson rush.\nVindication of the iso-says-they're-creating-just-not-finishing read.\n"
      },
      "newhook_winner": {
        "significance": "Hutson set up an entry, Newhook batted at a backhand from below the\ngoal line, the puck found a way past Vasilevskiy. Low-quality goal\nthat decides the series. Newhook is the L4 center promoted to that\nrole in G5; this is his second 5v5 series-winning shift.\n"
      },
      "zero_shots_p2": {
        "significance": "MTL's second period: zero shots on goal. Tampa took over the period\nafter the James PP goal. The Habs' game plan from then on was visibly\nshell up and trust Dobes. It worked.\n"
      },
      "outshot_9_29": {
        "significance": "The ratio of 9 shots for vs 29 against is one of the most extreme\noutshot Game 7 wins in modern playoff history. Most \"stolen\" Game 7s\nrun more like 18-30 — this was a complete defensive shell + a goalie\nstealing it.\n"
      },
      "series_competitiveness": {
        "significance": "Final series: all 7 games decided by 1 goal. 4 of 7 in OT. Combined\ngoal differential: 14-13 MTL. The most tightly contested R1 series\nacross the entire 2026 bracket — and decided by the rookie goalie at\nthe end.\n"
      }
    }
  },
  "interpretation": {
    "g7_recap": "Outshot 9-29. Won 2-1. Dobeš .966 in a Game 7 — the goalie heist that most rookies never get to author. Suzuki's L1 drought ended in P1, Newhook scored the winner from below the goal line in P3 on a backhand bat, and the Habs spent the second period without a single shot on goal.",
    "series_end": "All 7 games decided by 1 goal. 4 of 7 in OT. Most evenly contested R1 series in the bracket. Decided not by stars finally producing but by the rookie at the back finally stealing one — and a series-long run of low-event hockey that favored MTL's defensive shape.",
    "buf_preview_summary": "Buffalo enters R2 as the higher seed (Atlantic champ). They beat Boston 4-2 in 6 games on the back of Alex Lyon (.955 SV%, 4.6 GSAx — top-5 NHL playoff goalie). Their offense is led by Tuch and Thompson (7 pts each in 6 GP). Their D-corps is top-heavy: Dahlin + Byram are elite, Samuelsson + Power second pair, depth thin. Vulnerable in mid-pack 5v5 play-driving (xG share around break-even per Daily Faceoff). Strength: depth scoring (3 dangerous lines), shot-quality goaltending. Weakness: average 5v5 chance suppression behind their top D.",
    "matchup_thesis": "Habs vs Sabres is the meeting of two not-supposed-to-be-here teams. Both finished R1 with goalies stealing critical games (Dobeš G7, Lyon all 5 of his starts). MTL's iso math says Suzuki-Caufield-Slaf are net positives at 5v5; Buffalo's says Tuch + Thompson generate but get scored on. The matchup that matters: MTL's Hutson vs Buffalo's PP1 (Dahlin running the point). Both teams' R1 PP was their key differentiator vs goal differential."
  },
